      {
        "paragraph_index": 4,
        "text": "### Key Observations\n\n- **Ionic-strength dependence is pronounced:** The highest log β values correspond to the zero-ionic-strength (thermodynamic) extrapolations, while values at high I (3–4 M) can be either higher or lower depending on the medium and activity-coefficient model used.\n- **Entropy-driven complexation:** The positive ΔS values across all three species are consistent with the release of coordinated water molecules upon chloride binding — a hallmark of inner-sphere complex formation with Cd²⁺.\n- **Extensive coverage:** With 68 independent references, the Cd²⁺–Cl⁻ system is one of the most thoroughly studied halide–metal systems in the database, reflecting cadmium's environmental and electrochemical importance.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
